                <alternative value="excel">
                    <title>Excel 2013 and 2016 Instructions</title>
                    <p>Remember that to carry out the z-test in Excel, we first calculate the
                        z-statistic using the formula <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mover>
                                            <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                            <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                        </m:mover>
                                        <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                        <m:msub>
                                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                        </m:msub>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                    <m:mfrac>
                                        <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                        <m:msqrt>
                                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                        </m:msqrt>
                                    </m:mfrac>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Once you have calculated the z-statistic, you can calculate the p-value
                            using the Excel function <code style="inline">NORM.S.DIST</code>. In this
                            case, the p-value we want is <code style="inline"
                                >NORM.S.DIST(z-statistic, TRUE)</code>.</li>
                    </ul>
